31:26.418 --> 31:38.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now the next
conversation in
our occasional series in the
decades-old Israeli-Palestinian

31:38.363 --> 31:41.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
conflict that we are calling The
Long Divide.

31:41.933 --> 31:47.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight: whether there is reason
to be hopeful
that the peace process could
ever bear fruit.

31:47.105 --> 31:48.840 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And to John Yang.

31:48.874 --> 31:52.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: For that, we have
tonight two men
we have hosted on the "NewsHour"
many times

31:52.811 --> 31:54.880 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
over the years on this subject.

31:54.913 --> 31:59.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hisham Melhem is a columnist for
the Al-Arabiya
news channel in Washington,
D.C., and a correspondent

31:59.651 --> 32:05.524 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for the Lebanese daily newspaper
An-Nahar.
And David Makovsky is a -- was a
senior policy

32:05.557 --> 32:10.929 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
adviser to Secretary of State
John Kasich's
peace team for
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations

32:10.962 --> 32:17.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
during 2013 and 2014 and is a
long-serving
fellow at the Washington
Institute for Near

32:17.035 --> 32:18.770 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
East Policy.

32:18.804 --> 32:22.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To begin this series, Judy
Woodruff spoke
with Tom Friedman of The New
York Times. And

32:22.908 --> 32:25.510 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
here's a little bit of what Tom
had to say
about the peace process.

32:25.544 --> 32:29.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
THOMAS FRIEDMAN, The New York
Times: It's
actually been dead for a while.
I just called

32:29.514 --> 32:31.316 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it by its real name.

32:31.349 --> 32:36.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's clear to me, Judy, that
both sides have
conspired. This was like "Murder
on the Orient

32:36.988 --> 32:40.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Express." There were so many
stab wounds in
this body, hard to tell exactly
which one

32:40.725 --> 32:42.494 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
was the fatal blow.

32:42.527 --> 32:47.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: David, we quickly
heard from you
in disagreement. So, explain why
you disagree

32:47.465 --> 32:49.201 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
with Tom Friedman's analysis.

32:49.234 --> 32:51.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID MAKOVSKY, Senior Fellow,
Washington
Institute for Near East Policy:
No, I think

32:51.036 --> 32:54.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tom made a lot of good points,
so -- but I
think, the United States, we
have tried to

32:54.406 --> 33:00.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hit the home run ball three
times, Bill Clinton
in 2000, Condoleezza Rice in
2007-'8, and

33:00.979 --> 33:06.818 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the effort I was a part of with
Secretary
of State Kerry 2013-2014.

33:06.852 --> 33:12.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think what we see is that,
despite the
best efforts of the United
States, these guys

33:12.090 --> 33:17.929 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cannot do the home run ball. We
don't have
time to explain all the reasons,
but the point

33:17.963 --> 33:23.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is, is that I think we just have
to be more
modest in our objectives and try
to hit singles

33:23.134 --> 33:27.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and doubles, because whether
it's a lack of
leadership -- and, by the way,
even the great

33:27.339 --> 33:29.608 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
leaders in the Middle East
deferred these
issues.

33:29.641 --> 33:35.847 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a reason why these
issues -- the can's
been kicked down the road, and
we have disbelieving

33:35.881 --> 33:38.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
publics. They might say, I'm for
a two-state
solution, but I don't think the
other guy

33:38.850 --> 33:42.554 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is. And, third, we have got the
Middle East
in unprecedented turmoil, as the
"NewsHour"

33:42.587 --> 33:45.957 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has been chronicling, since the
Arab Spring
in 2011.

33:45.991 --> 33:50.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Taken all together, we could
just give up
and say let these guys kill each
other on

33:50.795 --> 33:55.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
both sides, or we could say
maybe we have
to be more modest in our
objectives, maintain

33:55.934 --> 34:00.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the viability of a two-state
solution, even
if we can't implement it, keep
that door open,

34:00.539 --> 34:02.974 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so when the sides want to go
through that
door, they can.

34:03.008 --> 34:04.542 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think there are some practical
ideas are
possible.

34:04.576 --> 34:06.645 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Hisham, is that
possible?

34:06.678 --> 34:09.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HISHAM MELHEM, Washington Bureau
Chief, Al-Arabiya
Television: Look, American
leadership is indispensable.

34:09.447 --> 34:11.283 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We have known that.

34:11.316 --> 34:15.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you leave the parties to
their own devices,
given the asymmetry between
Israel and the

34:15.654 --> 34:18.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Palestinians, given the fact
that Israel has
tremendous military
preponderance, strong

34:18.723 --> 34:24.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
economy, strong constitution,
you will end
up with two societies living
side by side

34:24.262 --> 34:32.337 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
unequal and resentful of each
other, and in
a state of constant
low-intensity violence.

34:32.370 --> 34:37.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if you allow the Israelis to
continue
settlement activities in
Palestinian territories,

34:37.442 --> 34:42.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
incorporating more Palestinian
lands, even
when you work on the limited
objectives, OK,

34:43.014 --> 34:46.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
then you will reach a point --
we may have
already reached it -- where
there will be

34:46.251 --> 34:48.186 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
nothing to divide.

34:48.219 --> 34:54.826 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have half-a-million Israelis
on Palestinian
land. And if you allow the
situation to continue,

34:54.859 --> 34:59.197 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
then it is impossible to talk
about two-state
solution, and you will end up in
a situation

34:59.230 --> 35:05.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where you have these two unequal
societies
living in a state of perpetual
low-intensity

35:05.971 --> 35:07.772 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
violence.

35:07.806 --> 35:13.244 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's the problem if you
maintain this
approach, let's contain it for a
while until

35:13.278 --> 35:15.880 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it ripens. But it may be too
late.

35:15.914 --> 35:19.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: David, given the
situation now,
they can't hit the long ball, as
you say.

35:19.584 --> 35:20.885 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Can they even hit the single or
the double?

35:20.919 --> 35:22.721 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID MAKOVSKY: Look, I don't
know, but we
have to try.

35:22.754 --> 35:28.326 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And my goal is not to contain or
to have a
status quo, but really to find a
way that

35:28.360 --> 35:33.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
basically you channel the
settlement enterprise
into an area we already know; 80
percent of

35:33.732 --> 35:40.271 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the settlers own 5 percent of
the land largely
adjacent to the Israeli urban
areas we used

35:40.305 --> 35:42.207 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to call the pre-1967 border.

35:42.240 --> 35:47.712 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And most of the Palestinians are
on the other
side of that. And so we kind of
know, territorially,

35:47.746 --> 35:52.150 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where this is going, and there
will be a land
exchange, what we call a
territorial swap.

35:52.183 --> 35:56.821 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, both sides know basically
what has to
be done. I do think you could
hit the single

35:56.855 --> 36:00.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or double. I just think the
stakes are so
high that, if we don't try, we
are basically

36:00.825 --> 36:02.961 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
consigning these people to
perpetual bloodshed.

36:02.994 --> 36:07.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if we try to hit the home
run ball a fourth
time, when we know these leaders
and publics

36:07.365 --> 36:09.901 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
can't do it, we're setting
ourselves up for
failure.

36:09.934 --> 36:14.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: But, Hisham, giving
up the settlement
blocs around the urban areas,
sounds like

36:14.239 --> 36:19.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that would be giving up East
Jerusalem. And
isn't the Palestinian goal of
having -- establishing

36:19.944 --> 36:22.947 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a capital in East Jerusalem?
Would that be
acceptable?

36:22.981 --> 36:24.849 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HISHAM MELHEM: Not to the
Palestinians, definitely.

36:24.883 --> 36:29.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, Palestinians would like
to have East
Jerusalem as their capital, just
as the Israelis

36:29.454 --> 36:34.259 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
could have West Jerusalem as
their capital.
This is a Palestinian position
that no Palestinian

36:34.292 --> 36:38.096 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
leaders can even entertain not
having or not
insisting upon that.

36:38.129 --> 36:43.635 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The problem of what we're having
here is,
there are structural problems in
the Israeli

36:43.668 --> 36:48.807 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
political culture. There are
powerful people
in Netanyahu's cabinet who are
calling for

36:48.840 --> 36:50.975 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
annexing the West Bank. It is
not only the
settlements.

36:51.009 --> 36:55.447 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They believe that the
Palestinians cannot
accept the Israeli presence or
existence,

36:55.480 --> 37:01.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and, essentially, they are
asking the Palestinians
to accept the impossible. There
are forces

37:02.020 --> 37:04.489 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
on both sides who are
maximalists now.

37:04.522 --> 37:09.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There was always a time when you
had an Israeli
constituency for peace and a
Palestinian constituency

37:09.527 --> 37:15.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for peace. These constituencies
have been
shrinking in the last few years.
And you have

37:15.533 --> 37:19.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the demonization taking place on
both sides
and maximalist positions on both
sides.

37:19.437 --> 37:23.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hamas lives in its own world.
You have an
ossified Palestinian leadership.
And you have

37:23.074 --> 37:29.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
an Israeli leadership that is
perpetuating
the status quo, unwilling or
unable, not courageous

37:29.047 --> 37:33.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
enough to make initiative, given
the fact
that Israel is the stronger
party.

37:33.485 --> 37:37.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And talking about the
situation
in Israel, are there Israelis
who are willing

37:37.489 --> 37:39.057 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to look for that single?

37:39.090 --> 37:40.024 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID MAKOVSKY: Yes.

37:40.058 --> 37:41.793 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Israeli leaders.

37:41.826 --> 37:44.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID MAKOVSKY: You see half of
the Knesset,
half of the Israeli parliament,
is talking

37:44.329 --> 37:46.131 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
about this openly.

37:46.164 --> 37:50.401 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And to your point on Jerusalem,
obviously,
Jerusalem has to be solved
between the parties.

37:50.435 --> 37:55.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can't find -- you can't
impose any solution
and you can't just let it kind
of unilaterally

37:55.240 --> 37:57.108 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
go in a certain director.

37:57.142 --> 38:01.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think there's ground rules
you could
set that -- in East Jerusalem
that would preserve

38:01.980 --> 38:07.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the outcome of a solution. And,
by the way,
if you look at some of the
positions, the

38:07.118 --> 38:11.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Palestinians know that the
Jewish neighborhoods
will be Israel and the
Palestinian neighborhoods

38:11.222 --> 38:12.524 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
will be Palestine.

38:12.557 --> 38:14.359 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
So I see...

38:14.392 --> 38:17.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HISHAM MELHEM: But you want to
hear an Israeli
leadership articulate a position
like -- you

38:17.495 --> 38:21.499 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
want to hear an Israeli leader
saying Jerusalem
should be shared.

38:21.533 --> 38:26.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You want to see an Israeli
leader saying,
this is our outlook and our
vision of eventual

38:26.204 --> 38:29.474 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
peace. They don't do that. They
keep kicking
the can down the road.

38:29.507 --> 38:32.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID MAKOVSKY: Part of the
problem is, you
have to realize, is these waves
of stabbings

38:32.944 --> 38:34.812 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that have radicalized the
situation.

38:34.846 --> 38:40.251 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have had like 180 stabbings
on the Palestinian
side that have convinced the
Israelis there

38:40.285 --> 38:42.921 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
is no partner, and the
Palestinians think,
we don't have a solution and we
will never

38:42.954 --> 38:43.721 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
get to a solution.

38:43.755 --> 38:45.423 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

38:45.456 --> 38:46.724 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Hisham Melhem, I'm
sorry. David
Makovsky, I'm afraid we have got
to leave

38:46.758 --> 38:48.092 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
